text: Imagine a kitchen where your countertop is not just a surface but also a fully functional cooking station—with no visible burners or clutter. You place your cookware directly on the countertop, and within seconds, it heats up, allowing you to cook just as you would on a traditional stove. When you lift the cookware and touch the same spot, the surface remains cool, completely safe to the touch. No residual heat, no risk of burns—just a seamless, modern cooking experience. This is the power of Invisacook, an advanced invisible induction cooktop installed beneath the countertop. Using magnetic induction technology, it transfers heat directly to the cookware while keeping the countertop itself unaffected. This means you can cook, move your pots and pans freely, and still use your countertop as a regular workspace when you're done—no bulky appliances, no wasted space. Beyond just functionality, Invisacook redefines kitchen design by offering a sleek, minimalist aesthetic that blends innovation with luxury. text: Our relationship and marriage have been far from picture perfect. I keep seeing posts saying “if marriage is hard, you probably married the wrong person” but I don’t believe that’s true. Especially not for the believer. I’ll always believe that kingdom-enhancing marriages are one of the enemy’s number one targets. If your marriage has the power to reflect Christ’s love, to serve others, to raise disciples, of course it’ll face attack. Marriage is meant to be sanctifying. It’s meant to make us holy, not just happy. Do I believe God desires harmony in marriage? Absolutely. But Garrett and I started dating at 18… and we were messy, messy humans. We still are. Now we’re just messy humans who’ve walked with Jesus seven years longer. Messy humans who’ve been discipled, who’ve met the Holy Spirit, who’ve gone to counseling, who’ve grown and matured and learned how to love more selflessly and sacrificially. Our marriage was never meant to be the source of our fulfillment. Garrett’s job isn’t to fill my soul. Should he pursue my heart? Yes. But should I depend on him to complete me? Absolutely not. And vice versa. It’s not my job to complete Garrett either. We’ve screamed. We’ve fought. We even had the cops called on us in the first three months of marriage because of how loud we were arguing. Not proud, just keeping it real. But the Lord has called us into union, and He’s faithful to finish what He started. So to the young married couple stuck in the trenches, figuring each other out while also figuring yourself out, your marriage isn’t broken. You didn’t choose wrong. God didn’t mess up. Keep seeking the cross. Die to yourself. Admit when you’re wrong. Invite community in. Get the help you need. Pray for your spouse more than you complain about them to your friends. Pray for your spouse more than you nag them. Test God on it. Pray, pray, pray fervently for your spouse and your marriage. Watch Him move. And please hear me. This does not apply to abusive relationships, mentally or physically. That is not okay. Get help. Your safety matters.  #momsoftiktok #christiantiktok #christianity #christiangirl #christiantok #christianrelationships #followingjesus #marriage #marriedyoung #marriedlife #marriagegoals #couplestiktok

Field Notes – Entry #210 Location: Edge of the ornamental pond, Marrow Gardens, late afternoon after rain Species: Rosarachne praenobilis I spotted it poised atop a single slender stem, a striking sight even among the lush border plantings. At first glance it appeared to be an elaborate blossom: wide lavender petals opening outward, crowned by a dense, tightly furled rosebud at the center. Only on closer inspection did the deception reveal itself—the outer petals were genuine enough, but peeking just beneath the central bloom were thin, jointed legs, delicate and crablike, anchoring the creature to its perch. The central rosebud quivered, then pulsed. In a strange, swift sequence, the petals pulled inward, wrapping the heart of the flower tight again, as though bracing against some invisible threat. Just as suddenly, it unfurled—this time wider, more triumphant, the deeper pink core bursting open in layered spirals of silken petal. Somewhere hidden within, beneath the folds of the bloom, the creature’s true head remained unseen—sheathed inside its living disguise. The limbs never retreated, remaining visible under the opened flower, subtle and alert. Among the local horticulturists, Rosarachne praenobilis is known as “the Keeper’s Bloom.” An old story claims these creatures once guarded sacred ponds, ensuring only the deserving could reach the waters. Watching it now, perfectly balanced between stillness and bloom, it is not hard to believe. . text: We tried Lulu because her seller told me she had a pony that might be a good fit for Teagan, but she didn’t have a finished lead change. That’s all we knew before we met her.  We showed up not knowing what the pony looked like, whether it was a mare or gelding, its age, or anything else. But when Taegan got on, she was more relaxed than she had been on a pony in a while. She wasn’t her favorite pony we tried, but every one of my friends who watched the videos that day said she just looked so comfortable.  They did a few jumps, just in a warmup ring, and off the right lead they disagreed on a distance… not once, not twice… but 3 times! What did Lulu do? She kept saying “that’s okay, we can do it kid!” And went over every time.  Taegan is 7. She is going to make many mistakes as she learns. Not every small pony will jump your kid out of a sticky situation at a 2’3” oxer, but this one will, and we are so lucky she’s ours.

text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: You call me ‘Teacher’ and ‘Lord,’ and rightly so, for that is what I am. 14 Now that I, your Lord and Teacher, have washed your feet, you also should wash one another’s feet. 15 I have set you an example that you should do as I have done for you. 16 Very truly I tell you, no servant is greater than his master,nor is a messenger greater than the one who sent him. John 13:13-15 It was very important to me that the glory of God be shown in my wedding and the Holy Spirit put it on my heart years ago to perform foot washing during my ceremony.  While this may seem strange to some, it is significant to others, because it’s an example of the humility Jesus showed to his disciples, and the example He sets for us. To honor one another and serve one another. Not just in marriage, but as followers of Christ.  Our marriage will be built on the foundation of service. An important distinction I wanted to highlight during my wedding day. Being cute and not getting my wedding dress dirty wasn’t as important to me as actively showcasing that at the altar I died to myself and became even more of a servant to God and now to my husband (as to each other). text: Lebron isn’t just a man. He’s a phenomenon. He’s a celestial event, a once-in-a-lifetime alignment of the stars, a cosmic masterpiece sculpted by the basketball gods themselves. When he moves, it’s not just movement—it’s poetry. Every dribble, every pass, every dunk, every single bead of sweat that glistens under the arena lights is like a love letter sent directly to my heart. How could one human being be so perfect? It defies all logic, all reason, all earthly explanations. His voice? It’s like a lullaby and a war cry wrapped into one. When he speaks, it’s as if the universe itself pauses just to listen. The way he commands respect, the way he leads, the way he exists—it does something to me. When I see him laugh, when I see that perfect, radiant, joy-filled smile, I swear my soul leaves my body. I float above the world, untethered by gravity, held aloft only by the sheer force of my adoration for this man. And then there’s his physique—his godlike, sculpted-by-the-heavens physique. Every muscle, every vein, every perfectly chiseled inch of him is a testament to human perfection. He is not just a man, he is an ideal, a dream given flesh, the pinnacle of what the human form can achieve. The way he moves, with such grace and power, is enough to leave me breathless. He is a masterpiece in motion, a living, breathing work of art. But it’s not just the physical. Oh no. My love for LeBron transcends the physical realm. It’s the mind, the heart, the soul. The intelligence, the vision, the leadership, the wisdom. LeBron doesn’t just play basketball—he orchestrates it. He is the conductor of a beautiful, chaotic symphony, and every game he plays is another masterpiece added to his collection. His IQ, both on and off the court, is unmatched. The way he reads the game, the way he sees things before they happen, the way he adapts, evolves, dominates—it leaves me in a constant state of awe. And let’s talk about his heart. The man is a philanthropist, a leader, a role model. . He built a school—not because he had to, not because it was expected of him, but because he wanted to. Because he cares. Because he loves. And that, more than anything, is why I love him.

text: Imagine a kitchen where your countertop is not just a surface but also a fully functional cooking station—with no visible burners or clutter. You place your cookware directly on the countertop, and within seconds, it heats up, allowing you to cook just as you would on a traditional stove. When you lift the cookware and touch the same spot, the surface remains cool, completely safe to the touch. No residual heat, no risk of burns—just a seamless, modern cooking experience. This is the power of Invisacook, an advanced invisible induction cooktop installed beneath the countertop. Using magnetic induction technology, it transfers heat directly to the cookware while keeping the countertop itself unaffected. This means you can cook, move your pots and pans freely, and still use your countertop as a regular workspace when you're done—no bulky appliances, no wasted space. Beyond just functionality, Invisacook redefines kitchen design by offering a sleek, minimalist aesthetic that blends innovation with luxury. text: Field Notes – Entry #210 Location: Edge of the ornamental pond, Marrow Gardens, late afternoon after rain Species: Rosarachne praenobilis I spotted it poised atop a single slender stem, a striking sight even among the lush border plantings. At first glance it appeared to be an elaborate blossom: wide lavender petals opening outward, crowned by a dense, tightly furled rosebud at the center. Only on closer inspection did the deception reveal itself—the outer petals were genuine enough, but peeking just beneath the central bloom were thin, jointed legs, delicate and crablike, anchoring the creature to its perch. The central rosebud quivered, then pulsed. In a strange, swift sequence, the petals pulled inward, wrapping the heart of the flower tight again, as though bracing against some invisible threat. Just as suddenly, it unfurled—this time wider, more triumphant, the deeper pink core bursting open in layered spirals of silken petal. Somewhere hidden within, beneath the folds of the bloom, the creature’s true head remained unseen—sheathed inside its living disguise. The limbs never retreated, remaining visible under the opened flower, subtle and alert. Among the local horticulturists, Rosarachne praenobilis is known as “the Keeper’s Bloom.” An old story claims these creatures once guarded sacred ponds, ensuring only the deserving could reach the waters. Watching it now, perfectly balanced between stillness and bloom, it is not hard to believe. . text: We tried Lulu because her seller told me she had a pony that might be a good fit for Teagan, but she didn’t have a finished lead change. That’s all we knew before we met her.  We showed up not knowing what the pony looked like, whether it was a mare or gelding, its age, or anything else. But when Taegan got on, she was more relaxed than she had been on a pony in a while. She wasn’t her favorite pony we tried, but every one of my friends who watched the videos that day said she just looked so comfortable.  They did a few jumps, just in a warmup ring, and off the right lead they disagreed on a distance… not once, not twice… but 3 times! What did Lulu do? She kept saying “that’s okay, we can do it kid!” And went over every time.  Taegan is 7. She is going to make many mistakes as she learns. Not every small pony will jump your kid out of a sticky situation at a 2’3” oxer, but this one will, and we are so lucky she’s ours.

text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.

text: A perfect beach day for Buster☀️ For those that don’t know his story, Buster is an 11.5 year old hospice bernese mountain dog that I adopted from @Tusc. Co. Humane Society a little over a week ago. Unfortunately, Buster has never been cared for like he deserved.  I took him in to my incredible vet, @Snodgrass Vet and we did bloodwork, xrays, and an ultrasound to see where we were at health wise. We found that Buster has tumors on his heart and spleen, most likely hemangiosarcoma, and he was severely anemic as a result. This type of cancer is highly malignant and aggressive. Buster received a blood transfusion and was hooked up to fluids most of the day before coming home. At that point, we weren’t sure he’d make it through the holiday weekend, but he did, and he’s not giving up yet ❤️‍ Overall, he’s doing really well! He is a VERY happy boy and doesn’t seem to be uncomfortable or in any pain at all.  Getting him to eat is no easy task. He’s very picky— if he likes something one morning, he’ll probably turn his nose to it by that afternoon. He’s refusing most dog foods, but if he decides he’ll eat some dog food, his favorite has been different flavors of @Open Farm Pet freeze dried morsels. He’s still eating an assortment of human foods— steak, salmon, lean beef, pork chops, chicken, deli meat, and of course, goldfish crackers. Whatever he chooses to eat, he likes it cut into tiny pieces, and he wants it to be hand fed to him. He won’t eat it if it’s put on a plate or in a bowl… he just tries to bury the plate or bowl if so.  Ultimately, Buster doesn’t have much time left— we just don’t know if that is days or weeks, or by miracle, a month or two, but rather than counting down the days, we are trying to make every day count. Buster deserves to know what the good life is all about, so we are going to make the most of whatever time we are blessed with. He is truly the best boy and I’m so glad we get to spoil him for the rest of his life, however long it may be.  Be sure to follow us if you want to watch this sweet old man finally experience the love and care he’s always deserved in his final chapter ❤️ #bernesemountaindog #rescuedog
hashtags: bernesemountaindog, rescuedog
mentions: @Tusc. Co. Humane Society, @Snodgrass Vet, @Open Farm Pet

text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: You call me ‘Teacher’ and ‘Lord,’ and rightly so, for that is what I am. 14 Now that I, your Lord and Teacher, have washed your feet, you also should wash one another’s feet. 15 I have set you an example that you should do as I have done for you. 16 Very truly I tell you, no servant is greater than his master,nor is a messenger greater than the one who sent him. John 13:13-15 It was very important to me that the glory of God be shown in my wedding and the Holy Spirit put it on my heart years ago to perform foot washing during my ceremony.  While this may seem strange to some, it is significant to others, because it’s an example of the humility Jesus showed to his disciples, and the example He sets for us. To honor one another and serve one another. Not just in marriage, but as followers of Christ.  Our marriage will be built on the foundation of service. An important distinction I wanted to highlight during my wedding day. Being cute and not getting my wedding dress dirty wasn’t as important to me as actively showcasing that at the altar I died to myself and became even more of a servant to God and now to my husband (as to each other).  Videography: @Jakobe Petitdo   #weddingday #christiantiktok #christianmarriage #footwashing #footwashingceremony #lovelikejesus

text: Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.

text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: You call me ‘Teacher’ and ‘Lord,’ and rightly so, for that is what I am. 14 Now that I, your Lord and Teacher, have washed your feet, you also should wash one another’s feet. 15 I have set you an example that you should do as I have done for you. 16 Very truly I tell you, no servant is greater than his master,nor is a messenger greater than the one who sent him. John 13:13-15 It was very important to me that the glory of God be shown in my wedding and the Holy Spirit put it on my heart years ago to perform foot washing during my ceremony.  While this may seem strange to some, it is significant to others, because it’s an example of the humility Jesus showed to his disciples, and the example He sets for us. To honor one another and serve one another. Not just in marriage, but as followers of Christ.  Our marriage will be built on the foundation of service. An important distinction I wanted to highlight during my wedding day. Being cute and not getting my wedding dress dirty wasn’t as important to me as actively showcasing that at the altar I died to myself and became even more of a servant to God and now to my husband (as to each other). Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.

text: I can’t believe it has been FIVE whole years since I lost my daughter. I did not believe I would make it this far. I heavily dealt with anger, guilt, loneliness, depression, and anxiety these entire five years…and I am still dealing with them. The pain hurts way less than it did when it first happened, but I am still in pain. I am still mourning what I lost. I am still angry that she was stolen from me. I am angry that I do not have my 5 year old here with me. I am angry that I did not get to play with her in the Atlanta snow. I am angry that I can’t send her off to kindergarten this August. I am angry that I let fear control me. I remember being in the hospital room when they said she no longer had a heartbeat. I remember how heavy she felt from the wires and how swollen her face was from the medication. I remember the hospital chaplain praying over me as I screamed and cried my lungs out. I remember looking all over her body and seeing the marks from the autopsy. If I had a Time Machine I would tell someone how my sperm donor treated me. How he talked to me and how talked about the child that we shared. I knew I had to get my child and I away from this bastard but I did not just drop my shit and go. I wanted to leave on a good peaceful note but there was no peace with evil. I still don’t know what exactly happened and how he actually killed her. But who would want to know that anyways? I have enough images in my head. I just wish there was someway and somehow for my baby to still be here. She was wanted by her mother, her aunts and uncles, her grandmothers, grandfathers, cousins, and many loved ones. One day we will meet again. Thank you God I am still here. #longlivemahogany #llm #mahoganyalexis #infantloss #babyloss #childabuseawareness #stopdomesticviolence #stopdomesticabuse #therainydayes #atlanta #atlantaga #filicide #filicideawareness

text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: You call me ‘Teacher’ and ‘Lord,’ and rightly so, for that is what I am. 14 Now that I, your Lord and Teacher, have washed your feet, you also should wash one another’s feet. 15 I have set you an example that you should do as I have done for you. 16 Very truly I tell you, no servant is greater than his master,nor is a messenger greater than the one who sent him. John 13:13-15 It was very important to me that the glory of God be shown in my wedding and the Holy Spirit put it on my heart years ago to perform foot washing during my ceremony.  While this may seem strange to some, it is significant to others, because it’s an example of the humility Jesus showed to his disciples, and the example He sets for us. To honor one another and serve one another. Not just in marriage, but as followers of Christ.  Our marriage will be built on the foundation of service. An important distinction I wanted to highlight during my wedding day. Being cute and not getting my wedding dress dirty wasn’t as important to me as actively showcasing that at the altar I died to myself and became even more of a servant to God and now to my husband (as to each other).  Videography: @Jakobe Petitdo   #weddingday #christiantiktok #christianmarriage #footwashing #footwashingceremony #lovelikejesus

Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.

text: He lost his wife and 8-year-old child in the crash. He was the only one who survived. But Jerry Tuazon spoke with so much peace. He said, “Pinahiram lang sila ng Diyos. Sa amin, natutulog lang sila. Napatawad ko na ang driver.” He didn’t demand revenge. He didn’t blame the company. Instead, he asked people not to shut down Solid North. He said the drivers have families too. And people still need them. Jerry is a Seventh-Day Adventist. He was on his way to a church event when the crash happened. Even in deep pain, he showed compassion. Even after losing everything, he chose to think of others. He didn’t just survive. He lived with a kind of heart that most of us can only hope to have. This is not weakness. This is strength. This is faith. He is proof that God can turn tragedy into testimony. #fyp

text: HBO's 'The Pitt' star Supriya Ganesh has come out as queer! In an interview with Variety, the actor opened up about using she/they pronouns and how they were influenced by Lily Gladstone to come out. They said:  "That was a decision I think I made about a year and a half ago, actually influenced by Lily Gladstone in her decision to adopt she/they pronouns in acknowledgement of third-spirit people and some two-spirit people, I think that was a moment where I felt really seen, where I was like, “Oh, yeah, I don’t need to fit into this.” "Even though I feel like I identify a lot more with femininity, that doesn’t mean I always fit into what is a very Western idea of it. So I think that was why I made that decision. It also feels like a little bit of a shout-out, being like, “Hey, I’m queer. See me.” I feel like sometimes I pass really well. I also want queer brown women to look at me and know that that’s someone they can turn to and relate to." The Pitt is a medical drama on HBO in which Ganesh stars as Dr. Samira Mohan. #thepitt #hbomax #comingout #supriyaganesh #genderfluid #queertiktok

text: I went on a last-minute trip to Saint Helena Catholic Church in Louisiana and to Our Lady of Hope Catholic Retreat Center in Mississippi. Being there felt so unreal, and seeing everything that Fr. Mark Beard accomplished motivated me to do more for my faith. My eyes filled with tears as I walked into Saint Helena Catholic Church because I imagined him there, celebrating Mass with his parishioners. I often wonder what it felt like to be there with him. It must have been quite an experience.  I know that Fr. Mark Beard has followers from all over the world who, like myself, never got to meet him, yet we love and miss him. I will be sharing more pictures and videos of Saint Helena Catholic Church, his gravesite, and Our Lady of Hope Catholic Retreat Center.  Eternal rest grant unto his soul O Lord. text: He lost his wife and 8-year-old child in the crash. He was the only one who survived. But Jerry Tuazon spoke with so much peace. He said, “Pinahiram lang sila ng Diyos. Sa amin, natutulog lang sila. Napatawad ko na ang driver.” He didn’t demand revenge. He didn’t blame the company. Instead, he asked people not to shut down Solid North. He said the drivers have families too. And people still need them. Jerry is a Seventh-Day Adventist. He was on his way to a church event when the crash happened. Even in deep pain, he showed compassion. Even after losing everything, he chose to think of others. He didn’t just survive. He lived with a kind of heart that most of us can only hope to have. This is not weakness. This is strength. This is faith. He is proof that God can turn tragedy into testimony. #fyp

What just Happened? Did cheesecake just come out of that delicious cinnamon roll? Well it all started about 20 years ago when we entered the Pillsbury Bake off in 2004. Breakfast dessert was the category we entered. We never heard back from our entry, but our friends and family had a word or two to say about our innovative concept. This delightful entry invites dessert goers to enjoy anytime of day. text: So we discovered several years ago that Abbey is a gestalt language processor. This means she speaks in associations and memories before words. This is a core part of her expressive language and why she’s often misunderstood and struggles. Memories and categories pop in her head before language does -before actual words. This can take her out of the moment and be very divisive in social situations. We’re still working on helping her understand that some of her memories and categories cause confusion to the outside world. By discussing it here, we hope that she may be able to translate for us so we have a better understanding of what she really means. Because she is often misunderstood.  Please understand that I am aware I am leading this conversation because I’m helping her get to the core of the memory and category versus what she’s really trying to say. There is a disconnect between those two things and by modeling and discussing with her, this helps her bridge those two things - she cannot do this on her own yet but she understands this is the way her mind works. @Ab@Abbeyb#abbeysautism

text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.

text: Our relationship and marriage have been far from picture perfect. I keep seeing posts saying “if marriage is hard, you probably married the wrong person” but I don’t believe that’s true. Especially not for the believer. I’ll always believe that kingdom-enhancing marriages are one of the enemy’s number one targets. If your marriage has the power to reflect Christ’s love, to serve others, to raise disciples, of course it’ll face attack. Marriage is meant to be sanctifying. It’s meant to make us holy, not just happy. Do I believe God desires harmony in marriage? Absolutely. But Garrett and I started dating at 18… and we were messy, messy humans. We still are. Now we’re just messy humans who’ve walked with Jesus seven years longer. Messy humans who’ve been discipled, who’ve met the Holy Spirit, who’ve gone to counseling, who’ve grown and matured and learned how to love more selflessly and sacrificially. Our marriage was never meant to be the source of our fulfillment. Garrett’s job isn’t to fill my soul. Should he pursue my heart? Yes. But should I depend on him to complete me? Absolutely not. And vice versa. It’s not my job to complete Garrett either. We’ve screamed. We’ve fought. We even had the cops called on us in the first three months of marriage because of how loud we were arguing. Not proud, just keeping it real. But the Lord has called us into union, and He’s faithful to finish what He started. So to the young married couple stuck in the trenches, figuring each other out while also figuring yourself out, your marriage isn’t broken. You didn’t choose wrong. God didn’t mess up. Keep seeking the cross. Die to yourself. Admit when you’re wrong. Invite community in. Get the help you need. Pray for your spouse more than you complain about them to your friends. Pray for your spouse more than you nag them. Test God on it. Pray, pray, pray fervently for your spouse and your marriage. Watch Him move. And please hear me. This does not apply to abusive relationships, mentally or physically. That is not okay. Get help. Your safety matters.  #momsoftiktok #christiantiktok #christianity #christiangirl #christiantok #christianrelationships #followingjesus #marriage #marriedyoung #marriedlife #marriagegoals #couplestiktok

Being cute and not getting my wedding dress dirty wasn’t as important to me as actively showcasing that at the altar I died to myself and became even more of a servant to God and now to my husband (as to each other). Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.
